<subSubSection lastPageId="74" lastPageNumber="75" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="73" pageNumber="74">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="74" lastPageNumber="75" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
The type is partially damaged: it lacks the right antenna and left flagellum. The type locality is different from the one given by du Buysson: Africa instead of Algeria. This information is particularly important, because the species has a typical sub-saharan aspect, and it does not belong to the Palaearctic fauna, as supposed by all 
<pageBreakToken pageId="74" pageNumber="75" start="start">the</pageBreakToken>
authors. 
<bibRefCitation author="Linsenmaier, W" journalOrPublisher="Entomofauna" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" pagination="1 - 210" title="Die Goldwespen Nordafrikas (Hymenoptera, Chrysididae)." volume="10" year="1999">Linsenmaier (1999</bibRefCitation>
: 45) in his last revision on the northern African species considered 
<taxonomicName authority="Latreille, 1802" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Hedychrum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hedychrum radoszkowskyi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="radoszkowskyi">Hedychrum radoszkowskyi</taxonomicName>
as belonging to the Egyptian fauna (sic!), known only from the type &quot;Mir nicht in Natura bekannt&quot;.
</paragraph>
